{"title_page": "List of University of Michigan law and government alumni", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n:''The parent article is at [[List of University of Michigan alumni]]''\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em;\" width=\"400px\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center; background:darkblue\" | <span style=\"color:gold;\">'''Academic unit key'''</span>\n|-\n| '''Symbol''' || '''Academic unit'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr>\n|-\n| ARCH || [[Taubman College of Architecture and Urban Planning|Taubman College]]\n|-\n| BUS || [[Ross School of Business]]\n|-\n| COE || [[University of Michigan College of Engineering|College of Engineering]]\n|-\n| DENT || [[The University of Michigan|School of Dentistry]]\n|-\n| GFSPP || [[The University of Michigan|Gerald R. Ford School of Public Policy]]\n|-\n| HHRS || [[Horace H. Rackham School of Graduate Studies]]\n|-\n| LAW || [[University of Michigan Law School|Law School]]\n|-\n| LSA || [[University of Michigan College of Literature, Science, and the Arts|College of LS&A]]\n|-\n| MED || [[University of Michigan Health System|Medical School]]\n|-\n| SMTD || [[University of Michigan School of Music|School of Music, Theatre and Dance]]\n|-\n| PHARM || [[The University of Michigan|School of Pharmacy]]\n|-\n| SED || [[University of Michigan School of Education|School of Education]]\n|-\n| SNRE || [[The University of Michigan|School of Natural Resources]]\n|-\n| SOAD || [[Penny W. Stamps School of Art & Design|The Stamps School of Art & Design]]\n|-\n| SOI || [[The University of Michigan|School of Information]]\n|-\n| SON || [[The University of Michigan|School of Nursing]]\n|-\n| SOK || [[The University of Michigan|School of Kinesiology]]\n|-\n| SOSW || [[University of Michigan School of Social Work|School of Social Work]]\n|-\n| SPH || [[University of Michigan School of Public Health|School of Public Health]]\n|-\n|-\n| MDNG || [[The University of Michigan|Matriculated, did not graduate]]\n|}\n\nThis is a partial list of notable alumni in law, government and public policy from the [[University of Michigan]]. Please refer also to the below list:\n\n==Legislators==\n{{Main|List of University of Michigan legislator alumni}}\n*[[Estefania Aldaba-Lim]] (Ph.D.), first female Filipino Cabinet secretary; social services and development secretary 1971\u20131977; first Filipino clinical psychologist; President of the [[Girl Scouts of the Philippines]]; first woman to become special ambassador to the United Nations (1979); UN Peace Medal Award\n*[[Justin Amash]] (B.A. 2002, J.D. 2005), lawyer, politician; [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Michigan's 3rd congressional district]]; [[Libertarianism|libertarian]]-oriented maverick<ref name=\"congress\">{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=A000367|publisher=bioguide.congress.gov|title=AMASH, Justin - Biographical Information|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/15/us/politics/15freshman.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jennifer | last=Steinhauer | title=Justin Amash, Republican Freshman, Bucks His Party | date=April 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1211/70145.html|publisher=politico.com|title=Amash casts himself in Paul's mold - POLITICO|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Donald M. Baker]] (B.A., M.A. economics 1952, J.D. 1956), major force in federal legislation on labor, education and poverty of the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s; chief counsel for the [[Office of Economic Opportunity]] under [[Sargent Shriver]] during the [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] administration; oversaw such landmark legislation as the [[Occupational Safety and Health Act]] of 1970, the [[Employee Retirement Income Security Act]] of 1974, key additions to the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964|Civil Rights Act]], the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] and many school busing, family planning, jobs and anti-poverty programs<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/01/AR2006120101719.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Patricia | last=Sullivan | title=Donald M. Baker; Helped Shape Social Legislation for 3 Decades | date=December 2, 2006}}</ref>\n*[[Andrea Barthwell]] (M.D. 1980), Deputy Director for Demand Reduction at the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]] (Drug Czar); resigned in July 2004 with an interest in running for United States Senate from Illinois\n*[[Alvin Morell Bentley]] (B.A. 1940, M.A. 1963), U.S. Representative from [[Michigan's 8th congressional district]] (1953\u20131961); wounded in the [[United States Capitol shooting incident (1954)|1954 Capitol shooting incident]]; member of the [[United States Foreign Service|Foreign Service]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Alvin Morell Bentley|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000391|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Bill Bogaard|William J. \"Bill\" Bogaard]] (J.D. 1965), mayor of [[Pasadena, California]] (1984\u20131986; 1999\u2013present); longest-serving mayor in city history<ref name=\"pasadenaweekly\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasadenaweekly.com/cms/story/detail/?id=4199&IssueNum=54|publisher=pasadenaweekly.com|title=www.pasadenaweekly.com/cms/story/detail/?id=4199&IssueNum=54|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"umich\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.umich.edu/historyandtraditions/students/Pages/ProfilePage.aspx?SID=18534&Year=1965|publisher=law.umich.edu|title=|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Howard L. Bost]] (Ph.D. 1955), historic architect of [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and job-related benefits for workers; U-M awarded him the nation's first doctorate in medical economics\n*[[Lyman James Briggs]] (M.A. in Physics, 1895), civil servant for the U.S. Government for 49 years; headed the [[Uranium Committee|Briggs Advisory Committee on Uranium]]; namesake of [[Lyman Briggs College]] at U-M<ref name=\"nap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nap.edu/readingroom.php?book=biomems&page=lbriggs.html|publisher=nap.edu|title=Biographical Memoirs Home|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[William J. Bulow]] (J.D. 1893), first Democratic [[governor of South Dakota]] (1927\u20131931); [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] (1931\u20131941)<ref name=\"congress2\">{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=b001055|publisher=bioguide.congress.gov|title=BULOW, William John - Biographical Information|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Arleigh Burke]] ([[Master of Science in Engineering|MSE]] 1931), [[United States Navy]] [[Admiral (United States)|admiral]]; World War II naval hero; served an unprecedented three terms as [[Chief of Naval Operations]] (1955\u20131961)<ref name=\"defense\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=717|publisher=defense.gov|title=www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=717|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"navy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/pers-us/uspers-b/burke.htm|publisher=history.navy.mil|title=photos/pers-us/uspers-b/burke|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Anson Burlingame]] (1838\u20131841), Congressional Representative from Massachusetts; attended Detroit branch of the University of Michigan; served in the State senate in 1852; elected as a candidate of the American Party to the Thirty-fourth Congress and as a Republican to the Thirty-fifth and Thirty-sixth Congresses (March 4, 1855 \u2013 March 3, 1861); appointed Minister to Austria March 22, 1861, but was not accepted by the Austrian Government because of certain opinions he was known to entertain regarding Hungary and Sardinia; Minister to China from June 14, 1861, to November 21, 1867; appointed December 1, 1867, by the Chinese Government its ambassador to negotiate treaties with foreign powers<ref>{{cite web|title=Anson Burlingame|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B001112|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Charles W. Burson]] (B.A. in Political Science, 1966), Senior Professor of Practice at the [[Washington University School of Law]]; Executive Vice President, General Counsel and Secretary at [[Monsanto Company]] (2001\u20132006); [[Tennessee Attorney General]] (1988\u20131997); [[Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States|chief of staff]] to [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Al Gore]] (1997\u20132001)<ref name=\"wustl\">{{cite web|url=http://law.wustl.edu/faculty/pages.aspx?id=5705|publisher=law.wustl.edu|title=WULS: Charles W. Burson|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Harry M. Daugherty]] (LL.B. 1881), [[United States Attorney General]]; famously [[campaign manager]] and close advisor to [[Warren G. Harding]]<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Historical Encyclopedia of U.S. Independent Counsel Investigations|author=Greenberg, G.S.|date=2000|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=9780313307355|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qOgCthdaJqIC&pg=PA86#v=onepage|page=86|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Donald McDonald Dickinson]] (J.D. 1867), [[United States Postmaster General]] under [[Grover Cleveland]]\n*[[Gerrit John Diekema]] (LAW: JD 1883), Congressional Representative from Michigan; member of the State house of representatives 1885\u20131891, serving as speaker in 1889; mayor of Holland in 1895; chairman of the Michigan Republican State central committee 1900\u20131910; delegate to the Republican National Convention in 1896; member of the Spanish Treaty Claims Commission from 1901 until he resigned in 1907; chairman of the Republican State central committee in 1927; appointed United States Minister to the Netherlands by President Hoover on August 20, 1929, and served until his death in The Hague, Netherlands, December 20, 1930;<ref>{{cite web|title=Gerrit John Diekema|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000336|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Gerald R. Ford]] (B.A. 1935, HLLD 1974), 38th [[President of the United States]] (1974\u20131977); 40th [[Vice President of the United States]] (1973\u20131974); [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|Minority Leader of the United States House of Representatives]] (1965\u20131973); U.S. Representative from [[Michigan's 5th congressional district]] (1949\u20131973)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gerald R. Ford|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=F000260|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Harold Ford Jr.]] (J.D. 1996), U.S. Representative from the [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]-based [[Tennessee's 9th congressional district]] (1997\u20132007)<ref>{{cite web|title=Harold Ford Jr.|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=F000262|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Dick Gephardt|Richard A. \"Dick\" Gephardt]] (J.D. 1965), President and CEO of the [[Gephardt Group]] lobbying firm; [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Minority Leader]] (1995\u20132003); [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Majority Leader]] (1989\u20131995); U.S. Representative from [[Missouri's 3rd congressional district]] (1977\u20132005); [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] city alderman (1971\u20131976); unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for President in [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1988|1988]] and [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2004|2004]]<ref name=\"congress3\">{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=g000132|publisher=bioguide.congress.gov|title=GEPHARDT, Richard Andrew - Biographical Information|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Stephen Goldsmith]] (J.D.), Professor of Practice at the [[Harvard Kennedy School of Government]]; chair of the [[Corporation for National and Community Service]]; [[Deputy Mayor of New York City]] (2010\u201311); [[mayor of Indianapolis]] (1992\u20131999); [[district attorney]] for [[Marion County, Indiana]] (1979\u20131990)<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markbergen/2011/09/01/a-sad-end-for-stephen-goldsmith/ | work=Forbes | first=Mark | last=Bergen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/05/nyregion/stephen-goldsmith-a-bloomberg-pick-resigns-as-deputy-mayor.html | work=The New York Times | first1=Javier C. | last1=Hernandez | first2=Michael | last2=Barbaro | title=Stephen Goldsmith, a Bloomberg Pick, Resigns as Deputy Mayor | date=August 4, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"harvard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/about/faculty-staff-directory/stephen-goldsmith|publisher=hks.harvard.edu|title=Harvard Kennedy School - Stephen Goldsmith|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Henry T. Hazard|Henry Thomas Hazard]] (LLD 1868), [[Mayor of Los Angeles]] (1889\u20131892)\n*[[Alexander W. Joel]] (J.D. 1987), Civil Liberties Protection Officer for the [[Office of the Director of National Intelligence]]<ref name=\"dni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dni.gov/joel_bio.htm|publisher=dni.gov|title=joel_bio|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Philip Lader]] (M.A. History 1967), [[United States Ambassador to the United Kingdom]] (1997\u20132001); Administrator of the [[Small Business Administration]] (1994\u20131997); House Deputy Chief of Staff and Deputy Director for Management of the [[Office of Management and Budget]] (1993\u20131994)<ref name=\"nelsonmullins\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nelsonmullins.com/attorneys/philip-lader|publisher=nelsonmullins.com|title=Philip Lader, Partner &raquo; Nelson Mullins Riley &amp; Scarborough, LLP - Attorneys at Law|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"businessweek\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=731921&ticker=WPP:LN&previousCapId=25067258&previousTitle=FOSUN%20INTERNATIONAL|publisher=investing.businessweek.com|title=Stocks - Bloomberg|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Robert Meeropol]] (1969, M.A. 1970), attorney; founder and executive director of the [[Rosenberg Fund for Children]] (1990\u2013present); son of [[Julius and Ethel Rosenberg]]<ref name=\"umich2\">{{cite web|url=http://michigantoday.umich.edu/94/Mar94/mt5m94.html|publisher=michigantoday.umich.edu|title=94/Mar94/mt5m94|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"rfc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rfc.org/robertsbiography|publisher=rfc.org|title=Robert Meeropol's Biography &#124; Rosenberg Fund for Children|accessdate=February 23, 2017|date=2008-10-30}}</ref>\n*William L. Mitchell (J.D.), former [[Kansas]] state legislator;speaker of the [[Kansas House of Representatives]] 1960\u20131962; served in the Kansas House 1957\u20131962; chairman of the Kansas Corporation Commission 1963\u20131968<ref name=\"kslib\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kslib.info/legislators/membm3.html|publisher=kslib.info|title=legislators/membm3|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Julius Sterling Morton]] (A.B. 1854), [[United States Secretary of Agriculture]] under President [[Grover Cleveland|Cleveland]]; created [[Arbor Day]]\n*[[Frank Murphy]] (J.D. 1914), [[United States Attorney General]] under [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]]; [[List of Justices of the Supreme Court of the United States|Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n*[[Thomas W. Palmer]] (MDNG) Senator from Michigan; member, State senate 1879\u20131880; elected as a Republican to the United States Senate and served from March 4, 1883, to March 3, 1889; appointed United States Minister to [[Spain]] in 1889 by President Benjamin Harrison and served for two years;<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas W. Palmer|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000044|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Edward Charles Pierce]] (BA 1955; MED: MD 1959), politician and physician; elected to the Michigan State Senate from the state's eighteenth district in 1978, and held the seat through 1982\n*[[L. Welch Pogue|Lloyd Welch Pogue]] (LAW: JD 1926), \"the nation's leading authority on civil aviation\"; named assistant general counsel of the Civil Aeronautics Authority in 1938, then its general counsel and chief lawyer; in 1942, President Franklin Roosevelt named Welch to the Civil Aeronautics Board (now the [[Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]]) and reappointed him chairman for four successive years\n*[[Harvey S. Rosen]] (A.B. 1970), Chair of President Bush's [[Council of Economic Advisers]]; deputy assistant secretary for tax analysis in the Department of the Treasury under President George H.W. Bush 1989\u20131991\n*[[Joe Schwarz]] (B.A. History 1959), Republican U.S. Congressman, MI-7th (2005\u20132007); Michigan State Senator (1987\u20132002)<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Schwarz|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S001161|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[George Sutherland]] (LAW: 1883), [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Associate Justice of the Supreme Court]]\n*[[Fred Upton]] (BA 1975), Republican U.S. Congressman, MI-6th (southwest Michigan)<ref>{{cite web|title=Fred Upton|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=u000031|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Arthur H. Vandenberg]] (LAW: JD), Republican US Senator; instrumental in creation of the [[United Nations]] in 1945; became chairman in 1947 of the [[U.S. Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], where he cooperated with the [[Harry S. Truman|Truman]] administration in forging bipartisan support for the [[Truman Doctrine]], the [[Marshall Plan]], and [[NATO]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Arthur H. Vandenberg|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=V000025|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Kapila Vatsyayan]] (MA), scholar of [[Indian classical dance]]; member of the [[Rajya Sabha]] (2006, 2007\u2013present)\n*[[James Franklin Ware]] (LAW: 1873), Wisconsin State Assemblyman and Senator\n\n==Governors and Lieutenant Governors==\n*[[Thomas Burton Adams Jr.]] was an American politician from the U.S. state of Florida. A Democrat, he served in the Florida Senate (1956\u20131960), as Secretary of State of Florida (1961\u20131971), and as the tenth Lieutenant Governor of Florida (1971\u20131975).\n*[[V\u00edctor Bravo Ahuja]], Mexican politician; academician; Secretary of Public Education in the administration of Luis Echeverr\u00eda (1970\u201376); Governor of Oaxaca\n*[[George Ariyoshi]] (J.D. 1952), third [[governor of Hawaii]] (1974\u20131986)<ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=John A. Burns: The Man and His Times|author1=Boylan, D.|author2=Holmes, T.M.|date=2000|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press|isbn=9780824822828|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ti5uYDfQ6IC&pg=PA125#v=onepage|page=125|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Diego Arria|Diego Enrique Arria Salicetti]], Governor of the Federal District of Caracas in the mid-1970s\n*[[Jos\u00e9 E. Benedicto]] was the Treasurer of Puerto Rico, and briefly served as acting Governor of Puerto Rico in 1921.\n*[[Theodore G. Bilbo]] was an American politician who twice served as governor of Mississippi (1916\u201320, 1928\u201332) and later was elected a U.S. Senator (1935\u201347). \n*[[Wilber Marion Brucker]] (A.B. 1916), [[List of Governors of Michigan|32nd Governor]] of Michigan 1931\u20131933; [[United States Secretary of the Army]] 1955\u20131961<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilber Marion Brucker|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_michigan/col2-content/main-content-list/title_brucker_wilbur.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[William John Bulow]] (LAW: JD 1893), Senator from South Dakota; member of State Senate 1899; mayor of Beresford 1912\u20131913; county judge of Union County, 1918; Governor of South Dakota 1927\u20131931; elected as a Democrat to the United States Senate in 1930; reelected in 1936 and served 1931\u20131943; chairman of Committee on the Civil Service (Seventy-third through Seventy-seventh Congresses)<ref>{{cite web|title=William John Bulow|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_south_dakota/col2-content/main-content-list/title_bulow_william.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[David Francis Cargo]] (BA 1951, MA 1953; LAW: LLB 1957), Governor of New Mexico, 1967\u201371; New Mexico State House of Representatives Albuquerque (1963\u201367)<ref>{{cite web|title=David Francis Cargo|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_new_mexico/col2-content/main-content-list/title_cargo_david.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Fenimore Chatterton]], Republican, governor of Wyoming (1903\u20131905)<ref>{{cite web|title=Fenimore Chatterton|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_wyoming/col2-content/main-content-list/title_chatterton_fenimore.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[John D. Cherry|John Cherry]] (MPA 1984), Lt. Governor of Michigan; former state senator\n*[[Chase Addison Clark]], Democrat, governor of Idaho (1941\u20131943)<ref>{{cite web|title=Chase A. Clark|url=http://www.fjc.gov