{"title_page": "Freinsheim", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox German location\n|type               = Stadt\n|image_photo       = Freinsheim BW 24.jpg\n|imagesize         = \n|image_caption     = Town hall and protestant church\n|image_coa            = DEU Freinsheim COA.svg\n|image_flag = Hissflagge Freinsheim.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|49|30|27|N|8|12|31|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = Freinsheim in D\u00dcW.svg\n|state        = Rheinland-Pfalz\n|district         = Bad D\u00fcrkheim\n|Verbandsgemeinde  = Freinsheim\n|elevation              = 72\n|area            = 13.61\n|population         = 4935\n|Stand             = 2007-12-31\n|postal_code               = 67251<br/> 67098 (Lindemannsruhe) <br/> 67247, 67248 (P.O. boxes)  \n|area_code           = 06353 <br/> 06322 (Lindemannsruhe)\n|licence               = D\u00dcW\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 07 3 32 019\n|website           = [http://www.stadt-freinsheim.de/ www.stadt-freinsheim.de]\n|mayor     = J\u00fcrgen Oberholz\n|party            = FWG\n}}\n'''Freinsheim''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8f\u0281a\u026ansha\u026am|lang}}; [[Palatine German language|Palatine German]]: '''Fr\u00e4nsem''') is a town in the [[Bad D\u00fcrkheim (district)|Bad D\u00fcrkheim]] district in [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[Germany]]. With about 5,000 inhabitants, it is among the state's smaller towns. It is also the seat of the [[Freinsheim (Verbandsgemeinde)|like-named ''Verbandsgemeinde'']], a kind of collective municipality.\n\n== Geography ==\nFreinsheim lies in the [[Upper Rhine Plain]] at the eastern edge of the [[Palatinate forest]], roughly 20&nbsp;km west of [[Ludwigshafen]] between [[Bad D\u00fcrkheim]] (about 6&nbsp;km to the southwest) and [[Gr\u00fcnstadt]] near the [[German Wine Route]]. Within town limits rises the Fuchsbach.\n\n== History ==\nAs established by various [[Archaeology|archaeological]] finds, Freinsheim's municipal area has been continuously settled by human beings for roughly 5,000 years. An organized community likely existed beginning in the 6th century, as witnessed by the discovery of a [[Merovingian dynasty|Merovingian]] linear graveyard. Freinsheim had its first documentary mention in 773 in the Wei\u00dfenburg Monastery's records (this place is now [[Wissembourg]] in [[Alsace]], [[France]]).\n\nIn the 15th century, Freinsheim passed to the [[Electorate of the Palatinate]], under whose care the existing fortifications were completed. The town wall's most recent building work is the ''\u00e4u\u00dferes Eisentor'' (\u201couter iron gate\u201d), finished in 1514. In 1689, Freinsheim sustained heavy destruction in the [[Nine Years' War]] (known in Germany as the ''Pf\u00e4lzischer Erbfolgekrieg'', or War of the Palatine Succession); only foundations were left standing. In the 18th century came reconstruction. Administrative functions within the Electorate of the Palatinate (such as the institution of an ''[[Amt (country subdivision)|Unteramt]]'') helped bring about an economic upswing. After the [[French Revolution]] and the [[Congress of Vienna]], Freinsheim passed to the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]] along with the rest of the [[Palatinate (region)|Palatinate]] on the [[Rhine]]\u2019s left bank. Until 1818, Freinsheim belonged to a ''[[Ganerbschaft]]'' (joint inheritance), which comprised the [[House of Leiningen|Leiningen]] villages of Leistadt, [[Herxheim am Berg]] and [[Kallstadt]] as well as the Electorate of the Palatinate villages of Freinsheim and [[Weisenheim am Sand]].<ref name=\"gan\">[http://www.archivdatenbank.lha-rlp.de/speyer/a/a.06/e6/fb/akten/3260/ Akten beim Landeshauptarchiv Speyer]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nA small number of immigrants are known to have moved from Freinsheim to [[Pennsylvania]] in the 18th century, including [[Henry Antes]], a leader of the [[Moravian Church]].<ref name=AntesNom>{{cite web|last=Noble|first=Timothy M.|title=Henry Antes House|url={{NHLS url|id=75001657}}|work=National Historic Landmark Nomination|publisher=U.S. National Park Service|accessdate=February 17, 2014|year=1991}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Second World War]], Freinsheim belonged to the newly founded [[States of Germany|federal state]] of [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]. It has been seat of the ''[[Verbandsgemeinde]]'' since 1972. With effect from 23 June 1979, given its historical importance, the Rhineland-Palatinate ''Landtag'' bestowed the title ''Stadt'' (\u201ctown\u201d) upon Freinsheim.\n\n== Politics ==\n\n=== Town council ===\nThe council is made up of 20 council members, who were elected at the municipal election held on 7 June 2009, and the honorary mayor as chairman.\n\nThe municipal election held on 7 June 2009 yielded the following results:<ref>Kommunalwahl Rheinland-Pfalz 2009, Gemeinderat auf [http://wahlen.rlp.de/kw/wahlen/2009/gemeinderatswahlen/ergebnisse/3320201900.html wahlen.rlp.de]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\" align=\"center\"\n| || [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] || [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] || [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|FDP]] || [[Free Voters|FWG]] || '''Total'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2009 || 8 || 5 || 2 || 5 || 20 seats \n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2004 || 8 || 7 || 1 || 4 || 20 seats \n|}\n\n=== Mayors ===\nMatthias Weber (FWG) was elected Stadtb\u00fcrgermeister in June 2016. He is the successor of J\u00fcrgen Oberholz (FWG).<ref>http://www.rheinpfalz.de/lokal/artikel/freinsheim-weber-wird-neuer-buergermeister/</ref>\n\n=== Coat of arms ===\nThe town's [[Coat of arms|arms]] might be described thus: Per fess azure a demi-lion rampant sinister Or armed, langued and crowned gules and argent an uppercase letter F of the third between two bunches of grapes in fess of the first.\n\nThe crowned lion symbolizes the historical connection with the [[Electorate of the Palatinate]], since this [[charge (heraldry)|charge]] was that state's emblem (although it is halved here), while the F is, of course, the town's initial. The two bunches of blue grapes stand for the local [[winegrowing]], which began quite early on with [[red wine]] varieties, which nowadays take up almost half of the cultivated vineyard area within the town.\n\nThe town's earliest seal comes from the early 15th century, and shows the arms borne by the local fiefholders, the Lords of Meckenheim. However, the current arms are based on the town's second seal, dating from 1446. Some versions since that time have shown roses instead of the grapes that appear now.\n\nHistorically, the [[Palatine Lion]] should be shown on a sable (black) field. When these arms were granted, though, the [[tincture (heraldry)|tincture]]s were not the traditional Palatine ones, but rather the Bavarian ones, as the town was part of the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]] at the time.\n\nThe arms have been borne since 1845.<ref>[http://www.ngw.nl/int/dld/f/freinshe.htm Description and explanation of Freinsheim's arms]</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Freinsheim Wappen am Rathaus.jpg|Town coat of arms\nFile:Hissflagge Freinsheim.svg|Town flag\nFile:Banner Freinsheim.svg|Town \"Banner\" (vertical flag for hoisting from a horizontal pole)\n</gallery>\n\n=== ''Verbandsgemeinde'' ===\nAs seat of the ''Verbandsgemeinde'' of Freinsheim, Freinsheim is home to its administration. Belonging to the ''Verbandsgemeinde'' are the municipalities of [[Bobenheim am Berg]], [[Dackenheim]], [[Erpolzheim]], [[Herxheim am Berg]], [[Kallstadt]], [[Weisenheim am Berg]] and [[Weisenheim am Sand]].\n\n=== Town partnerships ===\nFreinsheim fosters partnerships with the following places:\n*{{flagicon|France}} [[Marcigny]], [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]], [[France]]\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Buttst\u00e4dt]], [[S\u00f6mmerda (district)|S\u00f6mmerda]], [[Thuringia]]\n\n== Culture and sightseeing==\n\n=== Literature prize ===\nIn memory of one of Freinsheim's most important citizens, the ''Hermann-Sinsheimer-Preis'' has been awarded since 1983. Prizewinners thus far have been, among others, [[Siegfried Lenz]], [[Hilde Domin]], Carola Stern, [[Marcel Reich-Ranicki]] and [[Marion Gr\u00e4fin D\u00f6nhoff]].\n\n=== Buildings ===\n[[File:Freinsheim BW 17.jpg|thumb|The ''Eisentor'' in the town wall]]\n[[File:Freinsheim BW 16.jpg|thumb|Part of the town wall]]\n\n==== Town wall ====\nA particularity of Freinsheim is the [[Gothic architecture|Late Gothic]] town wall with its towers and gates, which has been almost wholly preserved and is roughly 1&nbsp;300&nbsp;m long. It forms the basis of the town's historical appearance. Worthiest of note is the outer gate at the ''Eisentor'' (\u201cIron Gate\u201d) with its flanking towers and the [[Electorate of the Palatinate]] coat of arms. The heart of the town is extraordinarily well restored.\n\n==== Protestant parish church ====\nThe old main church of Freinsheim was, until its destruction in 1689, probably a Late Gothic hall church. Today it has a flat ceiling. The lower floor of the tower is still [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]].\n\n==== Former castle ====\nThe moated castle, which was held by the Electorate of the Palatinate beginning in 1471, lies outside the town wall. The round moat is still filled with water today. The main building standing today is a private house from the early 19th century.\n\n==== Wayside shrine ====\nIn the vineyards on the road to Ungstein stands a Late Gothic [[Wayside shrine|''Bildstock'']] with a Crucifixion group in a frame with a pointed arch. It bears the name ''Schwarzes Kreuz'' (\u201cBlack Cross\u201d), after which one of Freinsheim's wineries has named itself.\n\n==== West tower ====\nThe Romanesque ''Westturm'' at the mountain graveyard south of and somewhat outside the town is a former entrance tower to the likewise Romanesque Chapel of Our Lady on the Mountain. Forms on the west portal suggest an origin in the mid 11th century. The original roofing is no longer present.<ref>Lit.: Eduard Finke, DIE ROMANISCHEN KIRCHT\u00dcRME IN DER PFALZ, Mainz 1994</ref>\n\n=== Regular events ===\n\n==== ''Rotweinwanderweg'' ====\nThe ''Rotweinwanderweg'' (\u201cRed Wine Trail\u201d) is held on the fourth weekend in January. It opens on the Friday at dusk with a torchlight hike on which log torches (''Schwedenfeuer'') are made. On the Saturday and Sunday, the hiking takes place in the daytime, during which local winemakers along the trail through the vineyards around Freinsheim offer hikers selected red wines and dishes to go with them.\n\n==== ''Freinsheimer Altstadtfest'' ====\nEach year on the first weekend in June, the Freinsheim Old Town Festival is held. Its motto is ''Wein und Kultur auf historischen Pl\u00e4tzen'' (\u201cWine and culture on historic squares\u201d). In this, the town of Freinsheim places much importance on sophisticated cultural performances, which are then presented at the marketplace, the ''Retzerhof'' or the ''Saarhof''. As a rule, the festival lasts from Friday to Sunday.\n\n==== ''Stadtmauerfest'' ====\nThe Town Wall Festival held on the third weekend in July in the historic gate is among the region's biggest wine festivals.\n\n==== ''Kulinarischer Weinwanderweg'' ====\nThe Culinary Wine Trail is held on the fourth weekend in September, running through the town's vineyards. Winemakers and gastronomical businesses offer traditional Palatine cooking, Mediterranean dishes, wine and [[Federweisser]].\n\n==== ''Weihnachtsmarkt'' ====\nThe Christmas Market on the four weekends in Advent attracts visitors with its Nativity scene, in which living animals are used.\n\n== Economy and infrastructure ==\n\n=== Economy ===\nAlthough [[winegrowing]] has been edging fruitgrowing out as the town's main agricultural endeavour since the mid 20th century, the town is nevertheless still the seat of one of Germany's great fruit juice producers. Today, Freinsheim is among the [[Palatinate (wine region)|Palatinate]]\u2019s biggest winegrowing centres. Because of the historic Old Town, meanwhile, [[tourism]] has also grown into an important economic factor.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[Freinsheim station]] is at the junction of the ''[[Palatine Northern Railway]]'' ([[Bad D\u00fcrkheim]]\u2013[[Gr\u00fcnstadt]]) and the Freinsheim\u2013Frankenthal [[railway]] line, affording direct links towards [[Neustadt Central Station|Neustadt]], [[Frankenthal Central Station|Frankenthal]] and, by way of [[Gr\u00fcnstadt station|Gr\u00fcnstadt]], to [[Monsheim station|Monsheim]] or [[Ramsen, Rhineland-Palatinate|Ramsen]].\n\nFrom both Neustadt and Frankenthal run long-distance links towards Mannheim, Saarbr\u00fccken and [[Mainz]].\n\nOver the nearby ''[[Bundesstra\u00dfe]]'' 271, Freinsheim is linked to the [[Autobahn]]en [[Bundesautobahn 6|A&nbsp;6]] ([[Mannheim]]\u2013[[Saarbr\u00fccken]]), [[Bundesautobahn 61|A&nbsp;61]] ([[Koblenz]]\u2013[[Speyer]]) and [[Bundesautobahn 65|A&nbsp;65]] ([[Ludwigshafen]]\u2013[[Karlsruhe]]).\n\nExcept on the main thoroughfares (''Landesstra\u00dfen'', or State Roads), the whole town is either a 30&nbsp;km/h zone or a zone with traffic-calming measures in place.\n\n== Famous people ==\n\n=== Sons and daughters of the town ===\n[[File:Philipp Lorenz Geiger.jpg|thumb|150px|Philipp Lorenz Geiger]]\n* [[Jacob Gottfried Weber]] (1779\u20131839), trained jurist, was a musician at the Mannheim Conservatory.\n* [[Philipp Lorenz Geiger]] (1785\u20131836), chemist and pharmacist\n* Philipp Tillmann (1809\u2013died after 1881), politician\n* [[Philipp Merkle]] (1811\u20131899), German-American Freethinker and preacher\n* Hermann Sinsheimer (1883\u20131950), journalist and jurist, was editor-in-chief of [[Simplicissimus]]; in his honour Freinsheim awards the ''Hermann-Sinsheimer-Preis''. In his ''Am Schwarzen Kreuz'' (\u201cAt the Black Cross\u201d) stories, Sinsheimer wrote down his memories of his childhood in Freinsheim.\n* Franz Lind (1900\u20131966), painter and sculptor\n* Manfred Scherer (1951\u2013&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;), politician (CDU)\n\n=== Famous people associated with the town ===\n* Emil Bert Hartwig (1907\u20131996), painter, student of the master Paul Klee, lived in Freinsheim and died there.\n* Friedrich Joss\u00e9 (1897\u20131994), painter and graphic artist, grew up in Freinsheim.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Hermann Sinsheimer: ''Gelebt im Paradies'', Beschreibung einer Kindheit und Jugend im Freinsheim des ausgehenden 19. Jahrhunderts. M\u00fcnchen 1953, {{ISBN|3-87629-099-6}}\n* Alexander Thon: ''Freinsheim''. In: J\u00fcrgen Keddigkeit (Hrsg.): ''Pf\u00e4lzisches Burgenlexikon''. Beitr\u00e4ge zur pf\u00e4lzischen Geschichte Bd. 12/2, Institut f\u00fcr Pf\u00e4lzische Geschichte und Volkskunde, Kaiserslautern 2002, S.&nbsp;135\u2013139, {{ISBN|3-927754-48-X}}.\n* Clemens J\u00f6ckle: ''Freinsheim''. Schnell & Steiner, Regensburg 1998\n* Eduard Finke: \" Die romanischen Kircht\u00fcrme in der Pfalz\", Mainz 1994, {{ISBN|3-929135-03-5}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.stadt-freinsheim.de/ Town\u2019s official webpage] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Bad D\u00fcrkheim (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bad D\u00fcrkheim (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox German location\n|type               = Stadt\n|image_photo       = Freinsheim BW 24.jpg\n|imagesize         = 300px\n|image_caption     = Town hall and protestant church\n|image_coa            = DEU Freinsheim COA.svg\n|image_flag = Hissflagge Freinsheim.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|49|30|27|N|8|12|31|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = Freinsheim in D\u00dcW.svg\n|state        = Rheinland-Pfalz\n|district         = Bad D\u00fcrkheim\n|Verbandsgemeinde  = Freinsheim\n|elevation              = 72\n|area            = 13.61\n|population         = 4935\n|Stand             = 2007-12-31\n|postal_code               = 67251<br/> 67098 (Lindemannsruhe) <br/> 67247, 67248 (P.O. boxes)  \n|area_code           = 06353 <br/> 06322 (Lindemannsruhe)\n|licence               = D\u00dcW\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 07 3 32 019\n|Adresse-Verband   = Bahnhofstra\u00dfe 12 <br/> 67251 Freinsheim\n|website           = [http://www.stadt-freinsheim.de/ www.stadt-freinsheim.de]\n|mayor     = J\u00fcrgen Oberholz\n|party            = FWG\n}}\n'''Freinsheim''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8f\u0281a\u026ansha\u026am|lang}}; [[Palatine German language|Palatine German]]: '''Fr\u00e4nsem''') is a town in the [[Bad D\u00fcrkheim (district)|Bad D\u00fcrkheim]] district in [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[Germany]]. With about 5,000 inhabitants, it is among the state's smaller towns. It is also the seat of the [[Freinsheim (Verbandsgemeinde)|like-named ''Verbandsgemeinde'']], a kind of collective municipality.\n\n== Geography ==\nFreinsheim lies in the [[Upper Rhine Plain]] at the eastern edge of the [[Palatinate forest]], roughly 20&nbsp;km west of [[Ludwigshafen]] between [[Bad D\u00fcrkheim]] (about 6&nbsp;km to the southwest) and [[Gr\u00fcnstadt]] near the [[German Wine Route]]. Within town limits rises the Fuchsbach.\n\n== History ==\nAs established by various [[Archaeology|archaeological]] finds, Freinsheim's municipal area has been continuously settled by human beings for roughly 5,000 years. An organized community likely existed beginning in the 6th century, as witnessed by the discovery of a [[Merovingian dynasty|Merovingian]] linear graveyard. Freinsheim had its first documentary mention in 773 in the Wei\u00dfenburg Monastery's records (this place is now [[Wissembourg]] in [[Alsace]], [[France]]).\n\nIn the 15th century, Freinsheim passed to the [[Electorate of the Palatinate]], under whose care the existing fortifications were completed. The town wall's most recent building work is the ''\u00e4u\u00dferes Eisentor'' (\u201couter iron gate\u201d), finished in 1514. In 1689, Freinsheim sustained heavy destruction in the [[Nine Years' War]] (known in Germany as the ''Pf\u00e4lzischer Erbfolgekrieg'', or War of the Palatine Succession); only foundations were left standing. In the 18th century came reconstruction. Administrative functions within the Electorate of the Palatinate (such as the institution of an ''[[Amt (country subdivision)|Unteramt]]'') helped bring about an economic upswing. After the [[French Revolution]] and the [[Congress of Vienna]], Freinsheim passed to the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]] along with the rest of the [[Palatinate (region)|Palatinate]] on the [[Rhine]]\u2019s left bank. Until 1818, Freinsheim belonged to a ''[[Ganerbschaft]]'' (joint inheritance), which comprised the [[House of Leiningen|Leiningen]] villages of Leistadt, [[Herxheim am Berg]] and [[Kallstadt]] as well as the Electorate of the Palatinate villages of Freinsheim and [[Weisenheim am Sand]].<ref name=\"gan\">[http://www.archivdatenbank.lha-rlp.de/speyer/a/a.06/e6/fb/akten/3260/ Akten beim Landeshauptarchiv Speyer]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nA small number of immigrants are known to have moved from Freinsheim to [[Pennsylvania]] in the 18th century, including [[Henry Antes]], a leader of the [[Moravian Church]].<ref name=AntesNom>{{cite web|last=Noble|first=Timothy M.|title=Henry Antes House|url={{NHLS url|id=75001657}}|work=National Historic Landmark Nomination|publisher=U.S. National Park Service|accessdate=February 17, 2014|year=1991}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Second World War]], Freinsheim belonged to the newly founded [[States of Germany|federal state]] of [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]. It has been seat of the ''[[Verbandsgemeinde]]'' since 1972. With effect from 23 June 1979, given its historical importance, the Rhineland-Palatinate ''Landtag'' bestowed the title ''Stadt'' (\u201ctown\u201d) upon Freinsheim.\n\n== Politics ==\n\n=== Town council ===\nThe council is made up of 20 council members, who were elected at the municipal election held on 7 June 2009, and the honorary mayor as chairman.\n\nThe municipal election held on 7 June 2009 yielded the following results:<ref>Kommunalwahl Rheinland-Pfalz 2009, Gemeinderat auf [http://wahlen.rlp.de/kw/wahlen/2009/gemeinderatswahlen/ergebnisse/3320201900.html wahlen.rlp.de]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\" align=\"center\"\n| || [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] || [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] || [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|FDP]] || [[Free Voters|FWG]] || '''Total'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2009 || 8 || 5 || 2 || 5 || 20 seats \n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2004 || 8 || 7 || 1 || 4 || 20 seats \n|}\n\n=== Mayors ===\nMatthias Weber (FWG) was elected Stadtb\u00fcrgermeister in June 2016. He is the successor of J\u00fcrgen Oberholz (FWG).<ref>http://www.rheinpfalz.de/lokal/artikel/freinsheim-weber-wird-neuer-buergermeister/</ref>\n\n=== Coat of arms ===\nThe town's [[Coat of arms|arms]] might be described thus: Per fess azure a demi-lion rampant sinister Or armed, langued and crowned gules and argent an uppercase letter F of the third between two bunches of grapes in fess of the first.\n\nThe crowned lion symbolizes the historical connection with the [[Electorate of the Palatinate]], since this [[charge (heraldry)|charge]] was that state's emblem (although it is halved here), while the F is, of course, the town's initial. The two bunches of blue grapes stand for the local [[winegrowing]], which began quite early on with [[red wine]] varieties, which nowadays take up almost half of the cultivated vineyard area within the town.\n\nThe town's earliest seal comes from the early 15th century, and shows the arms borne by the local fiefholders, the Lords of Meckenheim. However, the current arms are based on the town's second seal, dating from 1446. Some versions since that time have shown roses instead of the grapes that appear now.\n\nHistorically, the [[Palatine Lion]] should be shown on a sable (black) field. When these arms were granted, though, the [[tincture (heraldry)|tincture]]s were not the traditional Palatine ones, but rather the Bavarian ones, as the town was part of the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]] at the time.\n\nThe arms have been borne since 1845.<ref>[http://www.ngw.nl/int/dld/f/freinshe.htm Description and explanation of Freinsheim's arms]</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Freinsheim Wappen am Rathaus.jpg|Town coat of arms\nFile:Hissflagge Freinsheim.svg|Town flag\nFile:Banner Freinsheim.svg|Town \"Banner\" (vertical flag for hoisting from a horizontal pole)\n</gallery>\n\n=== ''Verbandsgemeinde'' ===\nAs seat of the ''Verbandsgemeinde'' of Freinsheim, Freinsheim is home to its administration. Belonging to the ''Verbandsgemeinde'' are the municipalities of [[Bobenheim am Berg]], [[Dackenheim]], [[Erpolzheim]], [[Herxheim am Berg]], [[Kallstadt]], [[Weisenheim am Berg]] and [[Weisenheim am Sand]].\n\n=== Town partnerships ===\nFreinsheim fosters partnerships with the following places:\n*{{flagicon|France}} [[Marcigny]], [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]], [[France]]\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Buttst\u00e4dt]], [[S\u00f6mmerda (district)|S\u00f6mmerda]], [[Thuringia]]\n\n== Culture and sightseeing==\n\n=== Literature prize ===\nIn memory of one of Freinsheim's most important citizens, the ''Hermann-Sinsheimer-Preis'' has been awarded since 1983. Prizewinners thus far have been, among others, [[Siegfried Lenz]], [[Hilde Domin]], Carola Stern, [[Marcel Reich-Ranicki]] and [[Marion Gr\u00e4fin D\u00f6nhoff]].\n\n=== Buildings ===\n[[File:Freinsheim BW 17.jpg|thumb|The ''Eisentor'' in the town wall]]\n[[File:Freinsheim BW 16.jpg|thumb|Part of the town wall]]\n\n==== Town wall ====\nA particularity of Freinsheim is the [[Gothic architecture|Late Gothic]] town wall with its towers and gates, which has been almost wholly preserved and is roughly 1&nbsp;300&nbsp;m long. It forms the basis of the town's historical appearance. Worthiest of note is the outer gate at the ''Eisentor'' (\u201cIron Gate\u201d) with its flanking towers and the [[Electorate of the Palatinate]] coat of arms. The heart of the town is extraordinarily well restored.\n\n==== Protestant parish church ====\nThe old main church of Freinsheim was, until its destruction in 1689, probably a Late Gothic hall church. Today it has a flat ceiling. The lower floor of the tower is still [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]].\n\n==== Former castle ====\nThe moated castle, which was held by the Electorate of the Palatinate beginning in 1471, lies outside the town wall. The round moat is still filled with water today. The main building standing today is a private house from the early 19th century.\n\n==== Wayside shrine ====\nIn the vineyards on the road to Ungstein stands a Late Gothic [[Wayside shrine|''Bildstock'']] with a Crucifixion group in a frame with a pointed arch. It bears the name ''Schwarzes Kreuz'' (\u201cBlack Cross\u201d), after which one of Freinsheim's wineries has named itself.\n\n==== West tower ====\nThe Romanesque ''Westturm'' at the mountain graveyard south of and somewhat outside the town is a former entrance tower to the likewise Romanesque Chapel of Our Lady on the Mountain. Forms on the west portal suggest an origin in the mid 11th century. The original roofing is no longer present.<ref>Lit.: Eduard Finke, DIE ROMANISCHEN KIRCHT\u00dcRME IN DER PFALZ, Mainz 1994</ref>\n\n=== Regular events ===\n\n==== ''Rotweinwanderweg'' ====\nThe ''Rotweinwanderweg'' (\u201cRed Wine Trail\u201d) is held on the fourth weekend in January. It opens on the Friday at dusk with a torchlight hike on which log torches (''Schwedenfeuer'') are made. On the Saturday and Sunday, the hiking takes place in the daytime, during which local winemakers along the trail through the vineyards around Freinsheim offer hikers selected red wines and dishes to go with them.\n\n==== ''Freinsheimer Altstadtfest'' ====\nEach year on the first weekend in June, the Freinsheim Old Town Festival is held. Its motto is ''Wein und Kultur auf historischen Pl\u00e4tzen'' (\u201cWine and culture on historic squares\u201d). In this, the town of Freinsheim places much importance on sophisticated cultural performances, which are then presented at the marketplace, the ''Retzerhof'' or the ''Saarhof''. As a rule, the festival lasts from Friday to Sunday.\n\n==== ''Stadtmauerfest'' ====\nThe Town Wall Festival held on the third weekend in July in the historic gate is among the region's biggest wine festivals.\n\n==== ''Kulinarischer Weinwanderweg'' ====\nThe Culinary Wine Trail is held on the fourth weekend in September, running through the town's vineyards. Winemakers and gastronomical businesses offer traditional Palatine cooking, Mediterranean dishes, wine and [[Federweisser]].\n\n==== ''Weihnachtsmarkt'' ====\nThe Christmas Market on the four weekends in Advent attracts visitors with its Nativity scene, in which living animals are used.\n\n== Economy and infrastructure ==\n\n=== Economy ===\nAlthough [[winegrowing]] has been edging fruitgrowing out as the town's main agricultural endeavour since the mid 20th century, the town is nevertheless still the seat of one of Germany's great fruit juice producers. Today, Freinsheim is among the [[Palatinate (wine region)|Palatinate]]\u2019s biggest winegrowing centres. Because of the historic Old Town, meanwhile, [[tourism]] has also grown into an important economic factor.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[Freinsheim station]] is at the junction of the ''[[Palatine Northern Railway]]'' ([[Bad D\u00fcrkheim]]\u2013[[Gr\u00fcnstadt]]) and the Freinsheim\u2013Frankenthal [[railway]] line, affording direct links towards [[Neustadt Central Station|Neustadt]], [[Frankenthal Central Station|Frankenthal]] and, by way of [[Gr\u00fcnstadt station|Gr\u00fcnstadt]], to [[Monsheim station|Monsheim]] or [[Ramsen, Rhineland-Palatinate|Ramsen]].\n\nFrom both Neustadt and Frankenthal run long-distance links towards Mannheim, Saarbr\u00fccken and [[Mainz]].\n\nOver the nearby ''[[Bundesstra\u00dfe]]'' 271, Freinsheim is linked to the [[Autobahn]]en [[Bundesautobahn 6|A&nbsp;6]] ([[Mannheim]]\u2013[[Saarbr\u00fccken]]), [[Bundesautobahn 61|A&nbsp;61]] ([[Koblenz]]\u2013[[Speyer]]) and [[Bundesautobahn 65|A&nbsp;65]] ([[Ludwigshafen]]\u2013[[Karlsruhe]]).\n\nExcept on the main thoroughfares (''Landesstra\u00dfen'', or State Roads), the whole town is either a 30&nbsp;km/h zone or a zone with traffic-calming measures in place.\n\n== Famous people ==\n\n=== Sons and daughters of the town ===\n[[File:Philipp Lorenz Geiger.jpg|thumb|150px|Philipp Lorenz Geiger]]\n* [[Jacob Gottfried Weber]] (1779\u20131839), trained jurist, was a musician at the Mannheim Conservatory.\n* [[Philipp Lorenz Geiger]] (1785\u20131836), chemist and pharmacist\n* Philipp Tillmann (1809\u2013died after 1881), politician\n* [[Philipp Merkle]] (1811\u20131899), German-American Freethinker and preacher\n* Hermann Sinsheimer (1883\u20131950), journalist and jurist, was editor-in-chief of [[Simplicissimus]]; in his honour Freinsheim awards the ''Hermann-Sinsheimer-Preis''. In his ''Am Schwarzen Kreuz'' (\u201cAt the Black Cross\u201d) stories, Sinsheimer wrote down his memories of his childhood in Freinsheim.\n* Franz Lind (1900\u20131966), painter and sculptor\n* Manfred Scherer (1951\u2013&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;), politician (CDU)\n\n=== Famous people associated with the town ===\n* Emil Bert Hartwig (1907\u20131996), painter, student of the master Paul Klee, lived in Freinsheim and died there.\n* Friedrich Joss\u00e9 (1897\u20131994), painter and graphic artist, grew up in Freinsheim.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Hermann Sinsheimer: ''Gelebt im Paradies'', Beschreibung einer Kindheit und Jugend im Freinsheim des ausgehenden 19. Jahrhunderts. M\u00fcnchen 1953, {{ISBN|3-87629-099-6}}\n* Alexander Thon: ''Freinsheim''. In: J\u00fcrgen Keddigkeit (Hrsg.): ''Pf\u00e4lzisches Burgenlexikon''. Beitr\u00e4ge zur pf\u00e4lzischen Geschichte Bd. 12/2, Institut f\u00fcr Pf\u00e4lzische Geschichte und Volkskunde, Kaiserslautern 2002, S.&nbsp;135\u2013139, {{ISBN|3-927754-48-X}}.\n* Clemens J\u00f6ckle: ''Freinsheim''. Schnell & Steiner, Regensburg 1998\n* Eduard Finke: \" Die romanischen Kircht\u00fcrme in der Pfalz\", Mainz 1994, {{ISBN|3-929135-03-5}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.stadt-freinsheim.de/ Town\u2019s official webpage] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Bad D\u00fcrkheim (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bad D\u00fcrkheim (district)]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freinsheim"}
{"title_page": "Journey into Medicine", "text_new": "{{short description|1947 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Journey into Medicine\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Willard Van Dyke]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Irving Jacoby\n| narrator       = Tony Kraber\n| starring       = [[James Karen]]\n| music          = [[Henry Brant]]\n| cinematography = [[Boris Kaufman]]\n| editing        = Aram Boyajian\n| studio         = [[United States Information Agency|United States Information Service]]\n| distributor    = [[U.S. Department of State]]\n| released       = {{film date|1947}}\n| runtime        = 40 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Journey into Medicine''''' is a 1947 American [[documentary film|documentary-style film]]. The film stars [[James Karen]] as Michael Kenneth Marshall, a young medical student who goes through medical training at Columbia and Cornell. During his internship in pediatrics, Marshall loses one of his patients, a young girl to [[diphtheria]]. This case inspires him to enroll in the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health|Johns Hopkins School of Public Health]] and pursue a career in public health. While studying at Johns Hopkins, Marshall helps battle an outbreak of diphtheria in [[Baltimore]], which confirms to him his chosen vocation.\n\nThe film was made by the [[United States Information Agency|United States Information Service]] for use by the U.S. State Department. The film was meant to be shown outside the United States as a promotional film for American medicine and public health efforts abroad.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atwater|first=R. M.|last2=Brown|first2=W. H.|last3=Calver|first3=H. N.|date=July 1, 1949|title=Journey into Medicine|journal=American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health|volume=39|issue=7|pages=947\u2013948|issn=0002-9572|doi=10.2105/ajph.39.7.947-b|pmid=18017047|pmc=1528278}}</ref> \n\nThe film was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"Oscars1948\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1948 |title=The 20th Academy Awards (1948) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 29, 2019 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]])}}</ref> The [[Academy Film Archive]] preserved ''Journey into Medicine'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Preserved Projects|url=http://www.oscars.org/academy-film-archive/preserved-projects?title=journey+into+medicine&filmmaker=&category=All&collection=All|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref> The film is part of the Academy War Film Collection, one of the largest collections of World War II era short films held outside government archives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Academy War Film Collection|url=http://www.oscars.org/film-archive/collections/academy-war-film-collection|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0039517|title=Journey into Medicine}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=JourneyIntoMedicine|name=Journey into Medicine (1947)}}\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1940s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white documentary films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n{{sci-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1947 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Journey into Medicine\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Willard Van Dyke]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Irving Jacoby\n| narrator       = Tony Kraber\n| starring       = [[James Karen]]\n| music          = [[Henry Brant]]\n| cinematography = [[Boris Kaufman]]\n| editing        = Aram Boyajian\n| studio         = [[United States Information Agency|United States Information Service]]\n| distributor    = [[U.S. Department of State]]\n| released       = {{film date|1947}}\n| runtime        = 40 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Journey into Medicine''''' is a 1947 American [[documentary film|documentary-style film]]. The film stars [[James Karen]] as Michael Kenneth Marshall, a young medical student who goes through medical training at Columbia and Cornell. During his internship in pediatrics, Marshall loses one of his patients, a young girl to [[diphtheria]]. This case inspires him to enroll in the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health|Johns Hopkins School of Public Health]] and pursue a career in public health. While studying at Johns Hopkins, Marshall helps battle an outbreak of diphtheria in [[Baltimore]], which confirms to him his chosen vocation.\n\nThe film was made by the [[United States Information Agency|United States Information Service]] for use by the U.S. State Department. The film was meant to be shown outside the United States as a promotional film for American medicine and public health efforts abroad.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atwater|first=R. M.|last2=Brown|first2=W. H.|last3=Calver|first3=H. N.|date=July 1, 1949|title=Journey into Medicine|journal=American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health|volume=39|issue=7|pages=947\u2013948|issn=0002-9572|doi=10.2105/ajph.39.7.947-b|pmid=18017047|pmc=1528278}}</ref> \n\nThe film was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"Oscars1948\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1948 |title=The 20th Academy Awards (1948) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 29, 2019 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]])}}</ref> The [[Academy Film Archive]] preserved ''Journey into Medicine'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Preserved Projects|url=http://www.oscars.org/academy-film-archive/preserved-projects?title=journey+into+medicine&filmmaker=&category=All&collection=All|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref> The film is part of the Academy War Film Collection, one of the largest collections of World War II era short films held outside government archives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Academy War Film Collection|url=http://www.oscars.org/film-archive/collections/academy-war-film-collection|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0039517|title=Journey into Medicine}}\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id=JourneyIntoMedicine|name=Journey into Medicine (1947)}}\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1940s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white documentary films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n{{sci-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Journey_into_Medicine"}
{"title_page": "Ben Lui", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Ben Lui (Beinn Laoigh)\n| photo = Ben_lui_northern_corrie.jpg\n| photo_caption = Coire Gaothaich on the northern side of Beinn Laoigh\n| elevation_m = 1130\n| elevation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/munros/ben-lui |title= walkhighlands Ben Lui |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |publisher=walkhighlands.co.uk |accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref>\n| prominence_m = 875\n| prominence_ref = <br><small>[[List of mountains of the British Isles by relative height|Ranked 15th]] in [[British Isles]]</small>\n| parent_peak = [[Ben More (Crianlarich)|Ben More]]\n| listing = [[Munro]], [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]]\n| translation = Hill of the calf\n| language = [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]]\n| pronunciation = {{IPA-gd|pe\u0272\u02c8l\u032a\u02e0\u0264j|lang|beinnlaoigh.ogg}}\n| location = [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling council area]] / [[Argyll and Bute]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Grampian Mountains]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NN266263\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 50\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Ben Lui''' ([[Scottish Gaelic]]: '''Beinn Laoigh''') is a [[mountain]] in the southern [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]] of [[Scotland]], at the head of Glen Fyne. It has five well-defined [[ridge]]s radiating out from the summit. Four [[Cirque|corrie]]s lie between the ridges; including Coire Gaothaich which lies on the northeast side of the mountain.\n\nBen Lui is the highest and most famous of a group of four [[Munro]]s that lie south of [[Glen Lochy]], and about 10&nbsp;km north of the top end of [[Loch Lomond]]. The other three peaks in the group are [[Beinn a' Chleibh]], [[Ben Oss]] and [[Beinn Dubhchraig]].\n\nThe Ben Lui range of peaks was formerly a [[National Nature Reserve]]. The cliffs and rocky outcrops are particularly moist, with lower than normal levels of [[acid]]ity in the [[soil]]. This leads to an unusually lush growth of mountain plants, with [[saxifrage]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]]s being especially evident.\n\nThe simplest and shortest ascent of Ben Lui may be made from Glen Lochy, near the point where the [[stream|burn]] of Eas Daimh flows into the Lochy. A path leads up through an area of [[forestry]] and then onto the northwest ridge, reaching the summit in just over 3&nbsp;km. Descent may be varied by visiting Beinn a\u2019 Chleibh, which lies 2&nbsp;km to the south west.\n\nAn approach from the east allows for appreciation of the mountain's most celebrated feature, the rocky circular bowl of Coire Gaothaich. One may either start from [[Tyndrum]] [[Tyndrum Lower railway station|Lower station]] or [[Dalrigh]] in [[Strath Fillan]]; tracks from both starting points merge, and follow Glen Cononish to the foot of Ben Lui. From here the route follows the northern ridge of the mountain, Stob Garbh, to the summit, the distance being about 9&nbsp;km. This route is particularly treacherous in winter, even as late as April, when the final third of the ascent is often extremely icy. Furthermore, it can be extremely difficult to navigate through the crags around the upper rim of the Coire Gaothaich in poor visibility.\n\nBy descending via the south east ridge the walker may elect to include Ben Oss (and possibly Beinn Dubhcraig) in the route before returning to the start. If transport can be arranged a reasonably fit [[hillwalking|hillwalker]] can traverse all four Munros of the Ben Lui group in a day.\n\nBen Lui stands at the Head of Glen Fyne.\n\nA lochan on the slopes of Ben Lui has been identified as the source of Scotland's longest river, the [[River Tay|Tay]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-tayside-central-12243508 | title=Source of River Tay 'pinpointed'| work=BBC News| date=2011-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*Computer generated summit panoramas [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas/GRW/Lui-N.gif North] [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas/GRW/Lui-S.gif South] [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas.html index]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070312204226/http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/reserve.asp?NNRId=38 Ben Lui NNR]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|56.39704|N|4.81110|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(NN266263)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n{{Scottish Munros section 1}}\n\n{{British hills}}\n\n[[Category:Munros]]\n[[Category:Marilyns of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of the Southern Highlands]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Stirling (council area)]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Argyll and Bute]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Lorne]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Mid Argyll and Cowal]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:One-thousanders of the British Isles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Ben Lui (Beinn Laoigh)\n| photo = Ben_lui_northern_corrie.jpg\n| photo_caption = Coire Gaothaich on the northern side of Beinn Laoigh\n| elevation_m = 1130\n| elevation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/munros/ben-lui |title= walkhighlands Ben Lui |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |publisher=walkhighlands.co.uk |accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref>\n| prominence_m = 875\n| prominence_ref = <br><small>[[List of mountains of the British Isles by relative height|Ranked 15th]] in [[British Isles]]</small>\n| parent_peak = [[Ben More]] Crainlarich\n| listing = [[Munro]], [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]]\n| translation = Hill of the calf\n| language = [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]]\n| pronunciation = {{IPA-gd|pe\u0272\u02c8l\u032a\u02e0\u0264j|lang|beinnlaoigh.ogg}}\n| location = [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling council area]] / [[Argyll and Bute]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Grampian Mountains]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NN266263\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 50\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Ben Lui''' ([[Scottish Gaelic]]: '''Beinn Laoigh''') is a [[mountain]] in the southern [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]] of [[Scotland]], at the head of Glen Fyne. It has five well-defined [[ridge]]s radiating out from the summit. Four [[Cirque|corrie]]s lie between the ridges; including Coire Gaothaich which lies on the northeast side of the mountain.\n\nBen Lui is the highest and most famous of a group of four [[Munro]]s that lie south of [[Glen Lochy]], and about 10&nbsp;km north of the top end of [[Loch Lomond]]. The other three peaks in the group are [[Beinn a' Chleibh]], [[Ben Oss]] and [[Beinn Dubhchraig]].\n\nThe Ben Lui range of peaks was formerly a [[National Nature Reserve]]. The cliffs and rocky outcrops are particularly moist, with lower than normal levels of [[acid]]ity in the [[soil]]. This leads to an unusually lush growth of mountain plants, with [[saxifrage]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]]s being especially evident.\n\nThe simplest and shortest ascent of Ben Lui may be made from Glen Lochy, near the point where the [[stream|burn]] of Eas Daimh flows into the Lochy. A path leads up through an area of [[forestry]] and then onto the northwest ridge, reaching the summit in just over 3&nbsp;km. Descent may be varied by visiting Beinn a\u2019 Chleibh, which lies 2&nbsp;km to the south west.\n\nAn approach from the east allows for appreciation of the mountain's most celebrated feature, the rocky circular bowl of Coire Gaothaich. One may either start from [[Tyndrum]] [[Tyndrum Lower railway station|Lower station]] or [[Dalrigh]] in [[Strath Fillan]]; tracks from both starting points merge, and follow Glen Cononish to the foot of Ben Lui. From here the route follows the northern ridge of the mountain, Stob Garbh, to the summit, the distance being about 9&nbsp;km. This route is particularly treacherous in winter, even as late as April, when the final third of the ascent is often extremely icy. Furthermore, it can be extremely difficult to navigate through the crags around the upper rim of the Coire Gaothaich in poor visibility.\n\nBy descending via the south east ridge the walker may elect to include Ben Oss (and possibly Beinn Dubhcraig) in the route before returning to the start. If transport can be arranged a reasonably fit [[hillwalking|hillwalker]] can traverse all four Munros of the Ben Lui group in a day.\n\nBen Lui stands at the Head of Glen Fyne.\n\nA lochan on the slopes of Ben Lui has been identified as the source of Scotland's longest river, the [[River Tay|Tay]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-tayside-central-12243508 | title=Source of River Tay 'pinpointed'| work=BBC News| date=2011-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*Computer generated summit panoramas [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas/GRW/Lui-N.gif North] [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas/GRW/Lui-S.gif South] [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/panoramas.html index]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070312204226/http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/reserve.asp?NNRId=38 Ben Lui NNR]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|56.39704|N|4.81110|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(NN266263)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n{{Scottish Munros section 1}}\n\n{{British hills}}\n\n[[Category:Munros]]\n[[Category:Marilyns of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of the Southern Highlands]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Stirling (council area)]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Argyll and Bute]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Lorne]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Mid Argyll and Cowal]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:One-thousanders of the British Isles]]\n", "name_user": "Grinner", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ben more link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Lui"}
{"title_page": "Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Species of reptile}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = July 2019}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name='iucnredlist.org'/> (most populous species)\n| image = Galapagos giant tortoise Geochelone elephantopus.jpg\n| image_alt = Adult Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise\n| genus = Chelonoidis\n| species = nigra<ref name='R2010'>{{Cite book |first=A.G.J. |last=Rhodin |first2=P.P. |last2=van Dijk |editor-last=Iverson |editor-first= J.B. |editor2-last=Shaffer |editor2-first=H.B |title=Turtles of the world, 2010 update: Annotated checklist of taxonomy, synonymy, distribution and conservation status |series=Turtle taxonomy working group |year=2010 |pages=33\u201334 |publisher=Chelonian Research Foundation |doi=10.3854/crm.5.000.checklist.v3.2010|isbn=978-0965354097 }}</ref> complex\n| authority = ([[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824b<ref name='Quoy b'/>)\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name='iucnredlist.org'/>\n| subdivision = ''See: [[List of species of Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise]]''\n* {{extinct}}''[[Chelonoidis nigra abingdonii|C. abingdonii]]''<br /><small>([[Albert G\u00fcnther|G\u00fcnther]], 1877)<ref name=\"Gunther 1877 85\">{{Harvnb|G\u00fcnther|1877|p=85}}</ref></small>\n* ''C. becki''<br /><small>([[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]], 1901)<ref name='R1901'/></small>\n* ''C. chathamensis''<br /><small>([[John Van Denburgh|Van Denburgh]], 1907)<ref name='VD1907'>{{cite journal|last=Van Denburgh|first =John|authorlink=John Van Denburgh |year=1907|title=Preliminary descriptions of four new races of gigantic land tortoises from the Galapagos Islands|journal= Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences |series=Series 4|volume= 1|pages=1\u20136 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/31599075\n|accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref></small>\n* ''C. darwini''<br /><small>(Van Denburgh, 1907)<ref name='VD1907'/></small>\n* ''C. duncanensis''<br /><small>([[Samuel Garman|Garman]], 1917)<ref name='Garman'>{{cite journal|last=Garman|first=Samuel|authorlink= Samuel Garman|year=1917| title=The Galapagos tortoises|journal= Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College|volume=30|issue= 4|pages=261\u2013296}}</ref></small>\n* ''C. hoodensis''<br /><small>(Van Denburgh, 1907)<ref name='VD1907'/></small>\n* {{extinct}}''C. nigra''<br /><small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1824b)<ref name='Quoy b'/></small>\n* ''C. phantastica''<small><br />(Van Denburgh, 1907)<ref name='VD1907'/></small>\n* ''C. porteri''<br /><small>(Rothschild, 1903)<ref name='R1903'>{{cite journal |last=Rothschild |first=Walter |authorlink=Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild |year=1903 |title=Description of a new species of gigantic land tortoise from Indefatigable Island |journal=Novitates Zoologicae |volume=10 |page=119 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/15771201\n|accessdate=2012-01-11 }}</ref></small>\n* ''C. vicina''<br /><small>(G\u00fcnther, 1875)<ref name='G1875'/></small>\n{{hidden end}}\n| synonyms = See section species\n}}\nThe '''Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise''' complex or '''Gal\u00e1pagos giant tortoise''' complex (''Chelonoidis nigra'' and related species) are the largest living species of [[tortoise]]. Modern Gal\u00e1pagos tortoises can weigh up to {{convert|417|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Guinness2002\">{{cite web|title=2002: Largest Tortoise|publisher=Official Guinness World Records|author=White Matt|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/60at60/2015/8/2002-largest-tortoise-392870|accessdate=2015-11-27|date=2015-08-18}}</ref> Today, giant tortoises exist on only two remote archipelagos: the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]] 1000&nbsp;km due west of mainland [[Ecuador]]; and ''[[Aldabrachelys gigantea]]'' of [[Aldabra]] in the [[Indian Ocean]], 700&nbsp;km east of [[Tanzania]].\n\nThe Gal\u00e1pagos tortoises are native to seven of the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]], a volcanic [[archipelago]] about {{convert|1000|km|mi|abbr=on|-1}} west of the Ecuadorian mainland. With lifespans in the wild of over 100 years, it is one of the longest-lived [[vertebrates]]. A captive individual lived at least 170&nbsp;years. Spanish explorers, who discovered the islands in the 16th century, named them after the Spanish ''[[wiktionary:gal\u00e1pago#Spanish|gal\u00e1pago]]'', meaning \"tortoise\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.galapagos.to/TEXTS/GALAPAGO.HTM |title=On the Origin of <s>Species</s> 'Gal\u00e1pago' |last1=Woram |first1=John |date= n.d.|website=Las Encantadas: Human and Cartographic History of the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands |publisher=Rockville Press, Inc. |access-date=21 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[Turtle shell|Shell]] size and shape vary between populations. On islands with humid highlands, the tortoises are larger, with domed shells and short necks; on islands with dry lowlands, the tortoises are smaller, with \"saddleback\" shells and long necks. [[Charles Darwin|Charles Darwin's]] observations of these differences on the [[second voyage of HMS Beagle|second voyage of the ''Beagle'']] in 1835, contributed to the [[Evolution|development of his theory of evolution]].\n\nTortoise numbers declined from over 250,000 in the 16th century to a low of around 3,000 in the 1970s. This decline was caused by [[overexploitation]] of the species for meat and oil, [[Habitat destruction|habitat clearance]] for agriculture, and introduction of non-native animals to the islands, such as rats, goats, and pigs. The extinction of most giant tortoise lineages is thought to have also been caused by predation by humans or human ancestors, as the tortoises themselves have no natural predators. Tortoise populations on at least three islands have become extinct in historical times due to human activities. Specimens of these extinct taxa exist in several museums and also are being subjected to DNA analysis. 10 species of the original 15 survive in the wild; an 11th species (''[[Chelonoidis abingdonii]]'') had only a single known living individual, kept in captivity and nicknamed [[Lonesome George]] until his death in June 2012. Conservation efforts, beginning in the 20th century, have resulted in thousands of [[Captive breeding|captive-bred]] juveniles being released onto their ancestral home islands, and the total number of the species is estimated to have exceeded 19,000 at the start of the 21st century. Despite this rebound, all surviving species are classified as \"threatened\" by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\n\n===Early classification===\nThe Gal\u00e1pagos Islands were discovered in 1535, but first appeared on the maps, of [[Gerardus Mercator]] and [[Abraham Ortelius]], around 1570.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stewart |first=P.D. |title=Gal\u00e1pagos: the islands that changed the world |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |year=2006 |page=43 |isbn=978-0-300-12230-5}}</ref> The islands were named \"Insulae de los Galopegos\" (Islands of the Tortoises) in reference to the giant tortoises found there.<ref name=Pritchard1996P17>{{Harvnb|Pritchard|1996|p=17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Jackson | first = Michael Hume | title = Gal\u00e1pagos, a natural history | publisher = University of Calgary Press | location = Calgary | year = 1993 | page = [https://archive.org/details/galapagos00mich/page/1 1] | isbn = 978-1-895176-07-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/galapagos00mich/page/1 }}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">The first navigation chart showing the individual islands was drawn up by the pirate [[Ambrose Cowley]] in 1684. He named them after fellow pirates or English noblemen. More recently, the Ecuadorian government gave most of the islands Spanish names. While the Spanish names are official, many researchers continue to use the older English names, particularly as those were the names used when Darwin visited. This article uses the Spanish island names.</ref>\n\nInitially, the giant tortoises of the Indian Ocean and those from the Gal\u00e1pagos were considered to be the same species. Naturalists thought that sailors had transported the tortoises there.<ref>{{Harvnb|Chambers|2004|p=27}}</ref> In 1676, the pre-Linnaean authority [[Claude Perrault]] referred to both species as ''Tortue des Indes''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Perrault| first =Claude|authorlink=Claude Perrault|year= 1676|title=Suite des memoires pour servir a l'histoire naturelle des animaux|publisher= Acad\u00e9mie de Sciences|location= Paris|pages=92\u2013205|language= French }}</ref> In 1783, [[Johann Gottlob Schneider]] classified all giant tortoises as ''Testudo indica'' (\"Indian tortoise\").<ref>{{cite book |last=Schneider |first=Johann Gottlob |authorlink=Johann Gottlob Schneider |year=1783 |language=German |title=Allgemeine Naturgeschischte der Schildkr\u00f6ten nebs einem systematischen Verzeichnisse der einzelnen Arten und zwey Kupfen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wl5HAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA355 |pages=355\u2013356 |location=Leipzig\n|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref> In 1812, [[August Friedrich Schweigger]] named them ''Testudo gigantea'' (\"gigantic tortoise\").<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schweigger|first = August Friedrich|authorlink=August Friedrich Schweigger|year=1812 |language=Latin|title=Prodromi monographiae chelonorum sectio prima|journal= Archivfur Naturwissenschaft und Mathematik |volume=1 |pages=271\u2013368; 406\u2013462 }}</ref> In 1834, [[Andr\u00e9 Marie Constant Dum\u00e9ril]] and [[Gabriel Bibron]] classified the Gal\u00e1pagos tortoises as a separate species, which they named ''Testudo nigrita'' (\"black tortoise\").<ref name='DB1834'>{{Cite book|last =Dum\u00e9ril|first=Andr\u00e9 Marie Constant|authorlink=Andr\u00e9 Marie Constant Dum\u00e9ril|author2=Bibron, Gabriel |authorlink2=Gabriel Bibron | year=1834| url=https://archive.org/details/erptologiegnral00bibrgoog |title=Erp\u00e9tologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale; ou, histoire naturelle compl\u00e8te des reptiles|publisher= Librarie Encyclop\u00e9dique de Roret|location= France|language= French}}</ref>\n\n[[File:RothschildTortoise.png|thumb|alt=Black and white photograph of Walter Rothschild straddling an adult Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise: Rothschild is a Victorian gentleman sporting a beard and top hat.|Walter Rothschild, cataloger of two Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise species]]\n\n===Recognition of subpopulations===\nThe first systematic survey of giant tortoises was by the zoologist [[Albert G\u00fcnther]] of the [[British Museum]], in 1875.<ref name='G1875'/> G\u00fcnther identified at least five distinct populations from the Gal\u00e1pagos, and three from the Indian Ocean islands. He expanded the list in 1877 to six from the Gal\u00e1pagos, four from the [[Seychelles]], and four from the [[Mascarene Islands|Mascarenes]]. G\u00fcnther hypothesized that all the giant tortoises descended from a single ancestral population which spread by sunken [[land bridge]]s.<ref>{{Harvnb|G\u00fcnther|1877|p=9}}</ref> This hypothesis was later disproven by the understanding that the Gal\u00e1pagos, Seychelles, and Mascarene islands are all of recent volcanic origin and have never been linked to a continent by land bridges.  Gal\u00e1pagos tortoises are now thought to have descended from a South American ancestor,<ref name=\"Caccone et al 1999\"/> while the Indian Ocean tortoises derived from ancestral populations on Madagascar.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Austin |first=Jeremy|author2=Arnold, E. Nicholas |year=2001|title=Ancient mitochondrial DNA and morphology elucidate an extinct island radiation of Indian Ocean giant tortoises (Cylindraspis)|journal= [[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B]]|volume=268|pages=2515\u20132523 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2001.1825 |issue=1485 |pmid=11749704 |pmc=1088909}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Austin |first=Jeremy|author2=Arnold, E. Nicholas |author3=Bour, Roger  |year=2003|title=Was there a second adaptive radiation of giant tortoises in the Indian Ocean? Using mitochondrial DNA to investigate speciation and biogeography of ''Aldabrachelys'' |doi=10.1046/j.1365-294X.2003.01842.x |journal=Molecular Ecology |volume=12 |pages=1415\u20131424 |pmid=12755871 |issue=6 }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 19th century, [[Georg Baur]]<ref name='B1889'/> and [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Walter Rothschild]]<ref name='R1901'>{{cite journal |last=Rothschild |first=Walter |authorlink=Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild |year=1901 |title=On a new land-tortoise from the Galapagos Islands |journal= Novitates Zoologicae |volume=8 |page=372 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3268176\n|accessdate=2012-01-11 }}</ref><ref name=\"R1903\"/><ref name='R1902'>{{cite journal |last=Rothschild |first=Walter |authorlink=Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild |year=1902 |title=Description of a new species of gigantic land tortoise from the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands |journal=Novitates Zoologicae|volume=9|page=619 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3269130\n|accessdate=2012-01-11 }}</ref> recognised five more populations of Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise. In 1905\u201306, an expedition by the [[California Academy of Sciences]], with [[Joseph R. Slevin]] in charge of reptiles, collected specimens which were studied by Academy herpetologist [[John Van Denburgh]]. He identified four additional populations,<ref name=\"VD1907\"/> and proposed the existence of 15 species.<ref name='Van Denburgh 1914'>{{cite journal|last=Van Denburgh|first=John|year=1914|title=The gigantic land tortoises of the Galapagos archipelago|journal=Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences |series=Series 4|volume=2|issue=1|pages=203\u2013374 |url=https://archive.org/stream/giganticlandtort01vand#page/n5/mode/2up}}</ref> Van Denburgh's list still guides the [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] of the Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise, though now 10 populations are thought to have existed.<ref name='R2010'/>\n\n===Current species and genus names===\nThe current specific designation of ''nigra'' (\"black\" \u2013 [[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824b<ref name='Quoy b'>{{cite book |last1=Quoy|first1=J.R.C.|last2=Gaimard|first2=J.P.|year=1824b|chapter=Sous-genre tortue de terre \u2013 ''testudo''. brongn. tortue noire \u2013 ''testudo nigra''. N.|editor-last=de Freycinet|editor-first=M.L.|title=Voyage autour du Monde&nbsp;... ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 sur les corvettes de L. M. \"L'Uranie\" et \"La Physicienne,\" pendant les ann\u00e9es 1817, 1818, 1819 et 1820|location=Paris|pages=174\u2013175|language=French}}</ref>) was resurrected in 1984<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pritchard|first=Peter Charles Howard|authorlink=Peter Pritchard|year=1984|title=Further thoughts on Lonesome George|journal= Noticias de Gal\u00e1pagos |volume=39|pages=20\u201323}}</ref> after it was discovered to be the senior [[synonym (biology)|synonym]] (an older taxonomic synonym taking historical precedence) for the then commonly used species name of ''elephantopus'' (\"elephant-footed\" \u2013 [[Richard Harlan|Harlan]], 1827<ref name='Harlan'>{{cite journal|last=Harlan|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Harlan|year=1827\n|title=Description of a land tortoise, from the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands, commonly known as the \"Elephant Tortoise\"\n|journal=Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia |volume=5|pages=284\u2013292\n|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/24657342\n|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref>). Quoy and Gaimard's Latin description explains the use of ''nigra: \"Testudo toto corpore nigro\"'' means \"tortoise with completely black body\". Quoy and Gairmard described ''nigra'' from a living specimen, but no evidence indicates they knew of its accurate provenance within the Gal\u00e1pagos \u2013 the locality was in fact given as California. Garman proposed the linking of ''nigra'' with the extinct [[Floreana Island tortoise|Floreana]] species.<ref name='Garman'/> Later, Pritchard deemed it convenient to accept this designation, despite its tenuousness, for minimal disruption to the already confused nomenclature of the species. The even more senior species synonym of ''californiana'' (\"californian\" \u2013 [[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824a<ref name='1824a'>{{cite journal|last=Quoy|first= J.R.C. |author2=Gaimard, J.P. |year=1824|title=Description d'une nouvelle esp\u00e8ce de tortue et de trois esp\u00e8ces nouvelles de scinques|journal= Bulletin des Sciences Naturelles et de G\u00e9ologie|volume= 1|pages= 90\u201391|language=French}}</ref>) is considered a ''[[nomen oblitum]]'' (\"forgotten name\").<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pritchard|first= Peter Charles Howard| title = Galapagos tortoise nomenclature: a reply|journal= Chelonian Conservation and Biology|year=1997| page =619|volume= 2}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, the Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise was considered to belong to the genus ''[[Geochelone]]'', known as 'typical tortoises' or 'terrestrial turtles'. In the 1990s, subgenus ''[[Chelonoidis]]'' was elevated to generic status based on [[phylogenetic]] evidence which grouped the South American members of ''Geochelone'' into an independent [[clade]] (branch of the [[tree of life (biology)|tree of life]]).<ref name = \"Le et al.\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.03.003 |url=http://www.iucn-tftsg.org/wp-content/uploads/file/Articles/Le_etal_2006.pdf |last=Le |first=Minh |author2=Raxworthy, Christopher J. |author3=McCord, William P. |author4=Mertz, Lisa |year=2006 |title=A molecular phylogeny of tortoises (Testudines:Testudinidae) based on mitochondrial and nuclear genes |journal=[[Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution]] |volume=40 |issue=2 |pages=517\u2013531 |pmid=16678445 |access-date=11 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316211953/http://www.iucn-tftsg.org/wp-content/uploads/file/Articles/Le_etal_2006.pdf |archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This nomenclature has been adopted by several authorities.<ref name='iucnredlist.org'>Tortoise & Freshwater Turtle Specialist Group. (2016). ''Chelonoidis nigra''. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species {{doi|10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-1.RLTS.T9023A97224409.en}}</ref><ref name='R2010'/><ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.vertebrate-zoology.de/vz57-2/57-2_Fritz_149-368.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110719112201/http://www.vertebrate-zoology.de/vz57-2/57-2_Fritz_149-368.pdf |url-status= dead |archive-date= 19 July 2011 |last1=Fritz |first1=U. |last2=Hava\u0161|first2=P.|year=2007|title=Checklist of Chelonians of the World|journal=Vertebrate Zoology|volume=57|issue=2|pages=149\u2013368\n|accessdate=2012-01-11 }}</ref><ref name='CITES Appendices I, II and III 2011'>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.cites.org/eng/app/index.php\n|title=CITES Appendices I, II and III 2011\n|date=22 December 2011\n|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref>\n\n===Species===\n{{Main|List of species of Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise}}\n[[File:Galapagos tortoise distribution map.svg|thumb|alt=A map of the Gal\u00e1pagos with labels for names of the islands and their native species of tortoise|[[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands|Gal\u00e1pagos archipelago]] annotated with ranges of currently recognised [[species of Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise]], islands with surviving species are shaded.]]\nWithin the archipelago, up to 15 species of Gal\u00e1pagos tortoises have been identified, although only 11 survive to this day. Six are found on separate islands; five of them on the volcanoes of [[Isabela Island (Gal\u00e1pagos)|Isabela Island]]. Several of the surviving species are seriously endangered.<ref name=\"Caccone et al 1999\"/> One of the species, ''[[Chelonoidis nigra abingdonii|C. abingdonii]]'' from [[Pinta Island]], is [[extinct]] since 2014. The last known specimen, named [[Lonesome George]], died in captivity on 24 June 2012; George had been mated with female tortoises of several other species, but none of the eggs from these pairings hatched. The species inhabiting [[Floreana Island]] (''G. nigra'')<ref name=\"Poulakakis et al 2015\">{{cite journal |last1=Poulakakis|first1=Nikos |last2=Glaberman|first2=Scott |last3=Russello|first3=Michael |last4=Beheregaray|first4=Luciano B. |last5=Ciofi|first5=Claudio |last6=Powell|first6=Jeffrey R. |last7=Caccone|first7=Adalgisa |title=Historical DNA analysis reveals living descendants of an extinct species of Galapagos tortoise|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=2008 |volume=105 |issue=40 |pages=15464\u201315469 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0805340105 |pmid=18809928 |pmc=2563078|bibcode=2008PNAS..10515464P}}</ref> is thought to have been hunted to extinction by 1850,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Broom|first=R.|year=1929|title=On the extinct Gal\u00e1pagos tortoise that inhabited Charles Island |journal=Zoologica |volume=9 |issue=8 |pages=313\u2013320}}</ref><ref name='S1986'/> only 15 years after [[Charles Darwin]]'s landmark visit of 1835, when he saw shells, but no live tortoises there.<ref name=sulloway>{{cite journal |last=Sulloway |first=F.J. |year=1984 |editor-last=Berry |editor-first=R.J |title=Evolution in the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands: Darwin and the Gal\u00e1pagos |journal=Biological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=21 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=29\u201360 | doi=10.1111/j.1095-8312.1984.tb02052.x }}</ref> However, recent DNA testing shows that an intermixed, non-native population currently existing on the island of Isabela is of genetic resemblance to the species native to Floreana, suggesting that ''G. nigra'' has not gone entirely extinct.<ref name=\"Poulakakis et al 2015\" /> The existence of the ''C. phantastica'' species of [[Fernandina Island]] is disputed, as it was described from a single specimen that may have been an artificial introduction to the island; however, a live female was found in 2019, likely confirming the species' validity.<ref name=Pritchard1996P63>{{Harvnb|Pritchard|1996|p=63}}</ref><ref name='Swingland 1989'/><ref name='MacFarland 1974'/><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/02/20/world/americas/ap-lt-ecuador-giant-tortoise.html|title=Tortoise Feared Extinct Found on Remote Galapagos Island|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=2019-02-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nPrior to widespread knowledge of the differences between the populations (sometimes called [[Race (biology)|races]]) from different islands and volcanoes, captive collections in zoos were indiscriminately mixed. Fertile offspring resulted from pairings of animals from different races. However, captive crosses between tortoises from different races have lower fertility and higher mortality than those between tortoises of the same race,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=MacFarland|first=Craig G. |author2=Villa, Jos\u00e9 |author3=Toro, Basilio  |year=1974b |title=The Gal\u00e1pagos giant tortoises (''Geochelone elephantopus''). Part II: Conservation methods |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=198\u2013212 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(74)90068-8}}</ref><ref name='ReferenceB'>{{cite journal\n|url=http://www.ciens.ula.ve/~cires/recol-v3n1a03.pdf\n|last=M\u00e1rquez\n|first=Cruz\n|author2=Fritts, Thomas H. |author3=Koster, Friedmann |author4=Rea, Solanda |author5=Cepeda, Fausto |author6= Llerena |author7= Fausto |last-author-amp= yes \n|year=1995\n|language=Spanish\n|title=Comportamiento de apareamiento al azar en tortugas gigantes. Juveniles en cautiverio el las Islas Gal\u00e1pagos\n|journal=Revista de Ecolog\u00eda Latinoamericana|volume=3|pages=13\u201318\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211052639/http://www.ciens.ula.ve/~cires/recol-v3n1a03.pdf\n|archivedate=11 February 2006\n|accessdate=2012-01-11\n}}</ref> and captives in mixed herds normally direct courtship only toward members of the same race.<ref name='ReferenceB'/>\n\nThe valid scientific names of each of the individual populations are not universally accepted,<ref name=\"Pritchard1996P49\"/><ref name='Swingland 1989'/><ref name='Fritts 1984'/><ref name='R. Perry pp. 145'/> and some researchers still consider each species to be a subspecies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ernst|first=Carl H.|author2=Barbour, Roger|year=1989|title=Turtles of the world|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press|isbn=978-0-87474-414-9|url=https://archive.org/details/turtlesofworld00erns}}</ref><ref name='Poulakakis 2008'>{{cite journal|last=Poulakakis|first=Nikos|author2=Glaberman, Scott |author3=Russello, Michael |author4=Beheregaray, Luciano B. |author5=Ciofi, Claudio |author6=Powell, Jeffrey R. |author7= Caccone, Adalgisa | year=2008|title=Historical DNA analysis reveals living descendants of an extinct species of Galapagos tortoise|journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume= 105|issue=40|pages=15464\u201315469|doi=10.1073/pnas.0805340105 |pmid=18809928 |pmc=2563078|bibcode=2008PNAS..10515464P}}</ref> The taxonomic status of the various races is not fully resolved.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zug|first= George R.|year= 1997|title=Galapagos tortoise nomenclature: still unresolved|journal= The Journal of Chelonian Conservation and Biology|volume= 2|issue= 4|pages=618\u2013619|hdl=10088/11695}}</ref>\n\n{{hidden begin|title=Species synonymy<ref name=Pritchard1996P49>{{Harvnb|Pritchard|1996|p=49}}</ref>}}\n* ''Testudo californiana'' <small><br />[[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824a<ref name='1824a'/> (''nomen oblitum'')</small>\n* ''Testudo nigra'' <small><br />[[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824b<ref name='Quoy b'/> (''nomen novum'')</small>\n* ''Testudo elephantopus'' <small><br />[[Richard Harlan|Harlan]], 1827<ref name='Harlan'/> (''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo nigrita'' <small><br />[[Andr\u00e9 Marie Constant Dum\u00e9ril|Dum\u00e9ril]] and [[Gabriel Bibron|Bibron]], 1834<ref name='DB1834'/> (''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo planiceps'' <small><br />[[John Edward Gray|Gray]], 1853<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gray |first=John Edward |authorlink=John Edward Gray |year=1853 |title=Description of a new species of tortoise (''Testudo planiceps''), from the Galapagos Islands |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |volume=21 |issue=1 |pages=12\u201313 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1853.tb07165.x |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30747129\n|accessdate=2012-01-11 }}</ref> (''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo clivosa'' <small><br />[[Samuel Garman|Garman]], 1917<ref name='Garman'/> (''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo typica'' <small><br />[[Samuel Garman|Garman]], 1917<ref name='Garman'/> (''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo (Chelonoidis) elephantopus'' <small><br />Williams, 1952<ref>{{cite journal|last=Williams|first=Ernest E.|author2=Anthony, Harold Elmer |author3=Goodwin, George Gilbert  |year=1952 |title=A new fossil tortoise from Mona Island West Indies and a tentative arrangement of the tortoises of the world |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=99 |issue=9 |pages=541\u2013560 |hdl=2246/418}}</ref></small>\n* ''Geochelone (Chelonoidis) elephantopus'' <small><br />[[Peter Pritchard|Pritchard]], 1967<ref name='P1967'>{{cite book |last=Pritchard |first=Peter Charles Howard |authorlink=Peter Pritchard |year=1967 |title=Living turtles of the world |publisher=TFH Publications |location=New Jersey |page=156}}</ref></small>\n* ''Chelonoidis elephantopus'' <small><br />Bour, 1980<ref name='B1980'>{{cite journal |last=Bour |first= R. |year=1980 |title=Essai sur la taxinomie des Testudinidae actuels (Reptilia, Chelonii) |language=French |journal=[[Bulletin du Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle]] |volume=4 |issue=2 |page=546 }}</ref></small>\n{{hidden end}}\n{{hidden begin|title=Subspecies synonymy (summary)<ref name='R2010'/>}}\n''C. n. nigra'' ([[Subspecies#Nominate subspecies|nominate subspecies]])\n* ''Testudo californiana'' <small><br />[[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant Quoy|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824a<ref name='1824a'/> (''nomen oblitum'')</small>\n* ''Testudo nigra'' <small><br />[[Jean Ren\u00e9 Constant|Quoy]] & [[Joseph Paul Gaimard|Gaimard]], 1824b<ref name='Quoy b'/> (''nomen novum'')</small>\n* ''Testudo galapagoensis'' <small><br />[[Georg Baur (paleontologist)|Baur]] 1889<ref name='B1889'/></small>\n''C. n. abingdoni''\n* ''Testudo ephippium''<br /><small>[[Albert G\u00fcnther|G\u00fcnther]], 1875<ref name='G1875'/> (partim, misidentified type specimen once erroneously attributed to what is now ''C. n. duncanensis'')</small>\n* ''Testudo abingdoni''<small><br />[[Albert G\u00fcnther|G\u00fcnther]], 1877<ref name=\"Gunther 1877 85\"/></small>\n''C. n. becki''\n* ''Testudo becki''<small><br />[[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]], 1901<ref name='R1901'/></small>\n''C. n. chathamensis''\n* ''Testudo wallacei''<small><br/>[[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] 1902<ref name='R1902'/> (''partim'', ''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo chathamensis''<small><br />[[John Van Denburgh|Van Denburgh]], 1907<ref name='VD1907'/></small>\n''C. n. darwini''\n* ''Testudo wallacei''<small><br/>[[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] 1902<ref name='R1902'/> (''partim'', ''nomen dubium'')</small>\n* ''Testudo darwini''<small><br />[[John Van Denburgh|Van Denburgh]], 1907<ref name='VD1907'/></small>\n''C. n. duncanensis''\n* ''Testudo ephippium''<br /><small>[[Albert G\u00fcnther|G\u00fcnther]], 1875<ref name='G1875'/> (''partim'', misidentified type)</small>\n* ''Geochelone nigra duncanensis''<small><br />[[Samuel Garman|Garman]], 1917<ref name='Garman'/> in [[Peter Pritchard|Pritchard]], 1996<ref name=Pritchard1996P49/>(''nomen nudum'')</small>\n''C. n. hoodensis''\n* ''Testudo hoodensis''<small><br />[[John Van Denburgh|Van Denburgh]], 1907<ref name='VD1907'/></small>\