/sports/w-baskbl/mtt/powell_nicole00.html Stanford University player profile]\n*{{WNBA player|nicole_powell}}\n*[http://www.wnba.com/features/awards05_mostimproved.html WNBA article on her winning the \"Most Improved Player\" Award in 2005]\n*[http://www.wnba.com/monarchs/news/Nicole_Powell_Homecoming.html Reprinted September 29, 2006 ''Arizona Republic'' article on being named grand marshal at her high school]\n\n{{Big West Conference women's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Sacramento Monarchs 2005 WNBA Champions}}\n{{2004 WNBA Draft}}\n{{WNBA Most Improved Player Award}}\n{{Pac-12 Conference Women's Basketball Player of the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Powell, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Turkey]]\n[[Category:American women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2003 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Sting players]]\n[[Category:Fenerbah\u00e7e women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Gonzaga Bulldogs women's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Grand Canyon Antelopes women's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:New York Liberty players]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks women's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Sierra Vista, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sacramento Monarchs players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Storm players]]\n[[Category:Stanford Cardinal women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Tulsa Shock players]]\n[[Category:UC Riverside Highlanders women's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Women's National Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Nicole Powell\n| image = \n| current_title = Head coach\n| current_team = [[UC Riverside Highlanders women's basketball|UC Riverside Highlanders]]\n| current_conference = [[Big West Conference]]\n| current_record = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|06|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Sierra Vista, Arizona]], U.S.\n| player_years1 = 2000\u20132004\n| player_team1 = [[Stanford Cardinal women's basketball|Stanford]]\n| player_years2 = 2004\n| player_team2 = [[Charlotte Sting]]\n| player_years3 = 2005\u20132009\n| player_team3 = [[Sacramento Monarchs]]\n| player_years4 = 2010\u20132012\n| player_team4 = [[New York Liberty]]\n| player_years5 = 2013\n| player_team5 = [[Tulsa Shock]]\n| player_years6 = 2014\n| player_team6 = [[Seattle Storm]]\n| player_positions = [[Guard (basketball)|Guard]]/[[Forward (basketball)|Forward]]\n| coach_years1 = 2013\u20132014\n| coach_team1 = [[Gonzaga Bulldogs|Gonzaga]] (asst.)\n| coach_years2 = 2014\u20132017\n| coach_team2 = [[Oregon Ducks|Oregon]] (asst.)\n| coach_years3 = 2017\u20132020\n| coach_team3 = [[Grand Canyon Antelopes women's basketball|Grand Canyon]]\n| coach_years4 = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team4 = UC Riverside\n| overall_record = {{Winning percentage|18|18|record=y}}\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Kristen Powell''' (born June 22, 1982) is an American basketball coach who is currently the head women\u2019s basketball coach at [[UC Riverside Highlanders women's basketball|University of California, Riverside]]. As a player, she had a standout collegiate career at [[Stanford University]], Powell had an 11-year [[WNBA]] career most notably with the [[Sacramento Monarchs]] where she was an All-Star and won a WNBA Championship. Powell also played professionally overseas for [[Fenerbah\u00e7e Women's Basketball|Fenerbah\u00e7e Istanbul]].<ref name=\"fenerbahce\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.swishappeal.com/2017/4/8/15226846/sources-grand-canyon-hires-nicole-powell-ncaaw|title=Sources: Lopes to hire Oregon assistant Nicole Powell|date=April 8, 2017|website=Swish Appeal|access-date=April 8, 2017}}</ref> Powell had previously served on the coaching staffs at Gonzaga, Oregon, and Grand Canyon before being named the head coach of UC Riverside in March 2020.\n\n==High school==\nBorn in [[Sierra Vista, Arizona]], Powell played for [[Mountain Pointe High School]] in Phoenix, where she was named a [[Women's Basketball Coaches Association|WBCA]] All-American. She also was named a 2000 Parade Magazine First Team All-American in 2000 and the Arizona Player of the Century by the Arizona Republic.  She participated in the 2000 [[Women's Basketball Coaches Association#WBCA High School All-America Game|WBCA High School All-America Game]] where she scored fourteen points.<ref name=\"WBCA Box Scores\"/>\n\nIn addition, Powell during her high school years earned all-region selection in both tennis and track, won the state badminton singles championships in 1997, 1999 and 2000, won the state discus title in 2000, and was an Arizona 5A doubles runner-up in tennis in 2000.\n\n==College==\nPowell played the [[Basketball#Positions|forward position]] for [[Stanford University]] women's [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] basketball team. During her tenure there, she broke many school records, was named an All-American three times, and won numerous awards. She majored in [[urban development|urban studies]].\n\nShe was the first women's basketball player in the history of what is now the [[Pac-12 Conference]] to have achieved multiple [[triple-double]] games (that is, 10 totals or more in three different statistical categories) during the same season. Powell has since been joined by two other players: [[Brittany Boyd]] of [[California Golden Bears women's basketball|California]], who recorded two triple-doubles in the 2014\u201315 season, and [[Sabrina Ionescu]] of [[Oregon Ducks women's basketball|Oregon]], who has had multiple triple-doubles in all four of her college seasons (four in 2016\u201317, six in 2017\u201318, eight in both 2018\u201319 and 2019\u201320).<ref name=\"NCAA records\">{{Cite web|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/w_basketball_RB/2020/Triple-Doubles.pdf |title=Division I Women's Basketball Triple-Doubles History |work=2019\u201320 NCAA Women's Basketball Records |publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] |date=2019 |accessdate=August 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28162685/the-ultimate-guide-oregon-women-basketball-star-sabrina-ionescu |title=The ultimate guide to Oregon women's basketball star Sabrina Ionescu |website=ESPN.com |date=February 24, 2020 |accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref> Powell and Ionescu are also the only NCAA Division I women's players to have recorded multiple triple-doubles in the [[NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|NCAA tournament]]; Powell had two consecutive triple-doubles in 2002, while Ionescu had one each in 2018 and 2019.<ref name=\"NCAA records\"/>\n\n==Coaching==\nPowell spent one season, 2013-14, at Gonzaga as an assistant coach for coach [[Kelly Graves]]. After Graves accepted the head coaching position for the [[University of Oregon]], Powell took the assistant coach position at Oregon for three years. The 2016-2017 season was the most successful under Powell's assistant coaching career; it included a top-five recruiting class in 2016, headlined by Ionescu; a run to the Elite 8 in the 2017 NCAA Tournament; winning 6 out of 23 games against Top 25 opponents; and finishing the season at #16. \n\nIn April 2017, Powell accepted the head coaching position at Grand Canyon University.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gculopes.com/coaches.aspx?rc=931&path=wbball|title=GCU Women's Basketball: Nicole Powell|publisher=GCULopes.com|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Stanford statistics===\nSource<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/stats/StatsSrv/careerplayer|title=NCAA Statistics|website=web1.ncaa.org|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Year\n|Team\n|GP\n|Points\n|FG%\n|3P%\n|FT%\n|RPG\n|APG\n|SPG\n|BPG\n|PPG\n|-\n|2001-02\n|Stanford\n|'''35'''\n|581\n|'''49.0%'''\n|'''42.0%'''\n|82.6%\n|9.3\n|'''6.3'''\n|1.6\n|0.3\n|16.6\n|-\n|2002-03\n|Stanford\n|23\n|432\n|48.1%\n|40.4%\n|'''87.5%'''\n|9.3\n|3.8\n|1.8\n|'''0.6'''\n|18.8\n|-\n|2003-04\n|Stanford\n|31\n|'''627'''\n|42.9%\n|36.0%\n|85.6%\n|'''11.2'''\n|4.1\n|'''1.9'''\n|0.5\n|'''20.2'''\n|-\n|Career\n|\n|89\n|1640\n|46.3%\n|39.3%\n|85.1%\n|10.0\n|4.9\n|1.8\n|0.5\n|18.4\n|}\n\n==WNBA career==\nPowell was picked No. 3 overall by the [[Charlotte Sting]] in the 2004 [[WNBA Draft]]. She was used by the Sting as a utility player, appearing in 31 games.\n\nOn March 3, 2005, she was traded to the [[Sacramento Monarchs]] in a multi-player deal. The trade greatly aided the Monarchs in the 2005 season while Powell enjoyed a breakout year and eventually was named the recipient of that year's [[WNBA Most Improved Player Award|WNBA's Most Improved Player award]]. She played a pivotal role in the Monarchs' 2005 [[WNBA Finals]] victory over the [[Connecticut Sun]].\n\nAlthough the Monarchs struggled in subsequent years, Powell's statistics continued to improve.  In 2009, with several of her teammates hobbled by injuries, Powell averaged 16.7 points per game and was the best free throw shooter in the WNBA with 97.9% of attempts made.  She also participated in the 2009 WNBA All-Star Game, where she scored 21 points off the bench.\n\nThe Monarchs ceased operations following their 2009 season.  The New York Liberty selected Nicole Powell with the first pick in the ensuing dispersal draft.  She was traded to the Tulsa Shock before the 2013 season and signed with the Seattle Storm before the 2014 season.\n\n==USA Basketball==\nPowell was a member of the [[USA Women's U18 and U19 teams|USA Women's U18]] team which won the gold medal at the FIBA Americas Championship in [[Mar Del Plata]], [[Argentina]]. The event was held in July 2000, when the USA team defeated Cuba to win the championship. Powell averaged 8.2 points per game and led the team in rebounding with 6.4 per game.<ref name=\"2000 U18\"/>\n\nPowell was named to the [[USA Women's U18 and U19 teams|USA Women's U19]] team which represented the USA in the 2001 U19 World's Championship, held in [[Brno, Czech Republic]] in July 2001. Powell scored 7.0 points per game, led the team in rebounding with 6.3 per game to help the USA team to a 6\u20131 record and the bronze medal.<ref name=\"2001 U19\"/>\n\nIn 2003, Powell helped the United States women's national basketball team win a [[silver medal]] at the [[Pan American Games]] in [[Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic]].<ref name=\"2003 Pan Am\"/> She also helped national teams win a [[bronze medal]] (in the [[Czech Republic]]) and a [[gold medal]] (in [[Argentina]]) at two other international tournaments.\n\n==International career==\nDuring the 2008\u20132009 and 2009\u20132010 WNBA off-season, Powell contributed to Fenerbah\u00e7e's victories each year in the Turkish women's basketball league championship.  In 2007\u20132008 she played for CSKA Moscow in Russia, in 2006\u20132007 for Perfumerias Halcon Avenida in Spain, in 2005\u20132006 for Fenerbah\u00e7e for the first time, also winning the country's championship, and 2004\u20132005 Basket Spezia in Italy. Now Powell is a player of Polish team \u2013 TS Wis\u0142a Krak\u00f3w.\n\n==Awards and achievements==\n* 2009 [[2009 WNBA All-Star Game|WNBA All-Star Selection]]\n* 2005 WNBA Most Improved Player\n\n== Head coaching record ==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start\n| type=coach\n| conference=\n| postseason=\n| poll=\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n| name=[[Grand Canyon Antelopes]]\n| startyear=2017\n| conference=[[Western Athletic Conference|WAC]]\n| endyear=2020\n|}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season = 2017\u201318\n | name = Grand Canyon\n | overall = 16\u201314\n | conference = 9\u20135\n | confst